h <i>wind</i> ‘wind’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’, but in some cases perhaps from any of the places mentioned at   Windle  ."]},{"name":"Windell","meanings":["English: variant of   Windle  .","Swedish: ornamental name composed of the element <i>vind</i> ‘wind’ + the suffix <i>-ell</i>, a derivative of the Latin adjectival ending <i>-elius</i>."]},{"name":"Whittinghill","meanings":["Perhaps English: habitational name from a lost or unidentified place. However, this surname is not found in the British Isles.","Alternatively, an Americanized form of a surname of German origin, presumably   Windle   2."]},{"name":"Windels","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Lothar.","German: patronymic from (a variant of) the personal name   Wendel  .","North German: metronymic from a short form of the female personal names <i>Windelheid</i> or <i>Windelmod</i>."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":2,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":37,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4,